8. Finite State Machine (FSM)

8.1 Program A — Storage A / Mempool A

A0: IDLE
A1: REQUEST_CREATED
A2: WAITING_OK
A3: WAITING_RESPONSE
A4: DONE
A5: ERROR

Transitions:

A0 --create_request--> A1
A1 --send_request_hash--> A2
A2 --receive_ok_hash--> A3
A3 --receive_response_hash--> A4
A* --timeout / invalid_hash / reject--> A5


---

8.2 Program B — Storage B / Mempool B

B0: IDLE
B1: REQUEST_RECEIVED
B2: VALIDATED
B3: EXECUTED
B4: RESPONDED
B5: ERROR

Transitions:

B0 --receive_request_hash--> B1
B1 --validate_permissions--> B2
B2 --execute_request--> B3
B3 --emit_response_hash--> B4
B* --timeout / invalid_permission / invalid_context--> B5


---

9. Full Deterministic Flow

1. A canonicalizes REQUEST.
2. A computes REQUEST_HASH.
3. A derives request_id via BIP32.
4. A sends REQUEST_HASH to B.
5. B verifies:
   - STORAGE_A_ID ∈ allowed_storage_ids
   - MEMPOOL_A_ID ∈ allowed_mempool_ids
   - REQUEST_HASH ∈ allowed_request_types
   - context hash valid
6. If valid, B emits OK_HASH.
7. B executes authorized logic.
8. B generates RESPONSE_HASH.
9. A receives RESPONSE_HASH.
10. Both record transition witness.


